      <p class="text">I use El Milagro from Chicago.  It's roughly 40 cents per package, which is 12 corn tortillas, and the only ingredients are corn and lime.  Has anyone had trouble with finding the sweet spot between the chips being too browned and the chips being too chewy?  If you don't cook them long enough, it's hard to chew the chips.  Am I not using enough oil?</p>
      <div class="footer meta">
            posted by
            <a href="http://community.apartmenttherapy.com/users/298017">dilcue</a>
            on <a href="#cid-1671178" name="cid-1671178" title="Link to this comment">01.09.13 <span>at</span> 11:52AM</a>
      </div> <!-- .footer -->
      </div>
    <div class="article comment" id="cid-1671254">
      <p class="text">I love to make baked tortilla chips, especially with grape seed oil. Does anyone know the best way to make chips with a hint of lime flavor? Is it to simply just squeeze some fresh lime juice on the tortillas before baking?! Thanks for the recipe and photos!</p>
      <div class="footer meta">
            posted by
            <a href="http://community.apartmenttherapy.com/users/492385">Kitchn fan</a>
            on <a href="#cid-1671254" name="cid-1671254" title="Link to this comment">01.09.13 <span>at</span> 12:43PM</a>
      </div> <!-- .footer -->
      </div>
    <div class="article comment" id="cid-1671262">
      <p class="text">To dilcue: I spray the tortillas lightly with canola cooking spray (rather than brushing them individually), then bake in a slow oven until lightly browned. THEN turn off the oven and let them sit till completely dry --- at least an hour or so. (It's similar to making meringues.) That should dry them out enough so that they aren't chewy. Hope that helps--</p>
      <div class="footer meta">
            posted by
            <a href="http://community.apartmenttherapy.com/users/112339">lolagilligan</a>
            on <a href="#cid-1671262" name="cid-1671262" title="Link to this comment">01.09.13 <span>at</span> 12:50PM</a>
      </div> <!-- .footer -->
      </div>
    <div class="article comment" id="cid-1671272">
      <p class="text">Try squeezing a little fresh lime over the chips for added flavor (and skip the salt)...</p>
      <div class="footer meta">
            posted by
            <a href="http://community.apartmenttherapy.com/users/487763">marge@oldtownflooring</a>
            on <a href="#cid-1671272" name="cid-1671272" title="Link to this comment">01.09.13 <span>at</span> 12:56PM</a>
      </div> <!-- .footer -->
      </div>
    <div class="article comment" id="cid-1671276">
      <p class="text">I would put a few drops of lime in with the oil before brushing of spraying.</p>
      <div class="footer meta">
            posted by
            <a href="http://community.apartmenttherapy.com/users/492389">debibr</a>
            on <a href="#cid-1671276" name="cid-1671276" title="Link to this comment">01.09.13 <span>at</span> 01:01PM</a>
      </div> <!-- .footer -->
      </div>
    <div class="article comment" id="cid-1671338">
      <p class="text">Great idea to mix the lime juice with the oil! I have my own mister so can make my own combination to spray on the chips. I like the idea of cutting down on the salt, too! Thanks for the tips!</p>
      <div class="footer meta">
            posted by
            <a href="http://community.apartmenttherapy.com/users/492385">Kitchn fan</a>
            on <a href="#cid-1671338" name="cid-1671338" title="Link to this comment">01.09.13 <span>at</span> 01:44PM</a>
      </div> <!-- .footer -->
      </div>
</div><!-- #comments -->



    </div>
